2026-04-16 12:22:04 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module internal battery positive connection / PCB trace', 'power supply module internal LED-resistor branch wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='From the latest observation, the internal wiring of the power supply module is clearly incorrect with respect to the intended schematic. The battery positive terminal is not connected to any cable or to the LED branch; only the battery negative is connected to the PSU Output Cable (−). The series resistor is connected to PSU Output Cable (+) on one side but is open on the other, and the green LED anode is floating while its cathode is tied to PSU Output Cable (−). This miswiring isolates the external circuit from the actual battery positive terminal, so no 12 V is ever delivered to the downstream control modules or the load, explaining why all control‑module LEDs and the lamp remain off. The green LED can still light due to some internal path involving the PSU outputs and LED/resistor, misleadingly indicating power even though the battery positive is not properly routed. The root cause is therefore a fault in the internal wiring/PCB trace of the power supply module, specifically the missing connection from the battery positive terminal to the PSU Output Cable (+) and to the LED‑resistor network. Repairing or replacing this power supply module to restore the correct connections should fix the system.'
